    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "yeah the ice thing sounds scary. what happens if it happens mid-flight? does the pilot just lose all their speed info instantly?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If ice forms on the pitot tube mid-flight, the pilot doesn't just lose speed info; they lose *accurate* speed info, which is much more dangerous. The ice acts like a physical plug, preventing the tube from sensing the dynamic pressure correctly. The airspeed indicator will likely show an incorrect, often lower, reading, or it might even become erratic, depending on how completely it's blocked. This is why de-icing procedures are so critical before flight, and sometimes even in flight if conditions allow.",
      "source": "target",
